<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 92 / Shop centres report last-minute boost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY, IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, CHRIS TIGHE and JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SALES at the Bullring in Birmingham
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
one of Britain's biggest shoping centres - were expected yesterday to end
the Christmas period only about 2 per cent below last year. A surge in the
number of shoppers across the country provided an unexpected Christmas bonus
for retailers.
Bullring manager Mr Richard Cooke said that Christmas trading had got off to
a disappointing start in November and early December.
Many retailers said that more shoppers than normal had saved their buying
until the final week. In most parts, shops and shopping centres said they
expected results to be at worst similar to last year, and perhaps better.
Mr Grenville Peacock, chief executive of the Bentalls chain of stores in
south-east England, said large numbers of shoppers were out yesterday,
although average transactions might turn out to be down between 10 per cent
and 15 per cent compared with last year.
Central London was busier than it had been all year, although a series of
bomb scares closed Tube stations around Oxford Street.
Mr Andrew Bauer, manager of Whiteleys shopping centre in Bayswater, west
London, said there was 'a heck of a lot of last-minute buying going on. We
opened early today and thank goodness we did. People were waiting to get
in.'
He said shoppers were targeting their spending very carefully, having spent
weeks window-shopping.
Mr Alan Witkin, chairman of the tenants' association at Brent Cross shopping
centre in north London, said a 'Christmas finale' was under way, with car
parks and shops full.
In northern England, the news was even better. Mr Peter Hills, head of
marketing at Manchester Chamber of Commerce, said there had been a big surge
of business. Two days had been lost because of the IRA bombings in early
December, 'but there has been a tremendous recovery, with several record
days', he said.
Mr Bill Russell, assistant manager of Liverpool's Clayton Square shopping
centre, said trade was going well. 'Liverpool has had economic problems for
many years, but Merseyside people really enjoy Christmas and always go out
and spend on their children.'
Across the Pennines, Mr Peter Coles-Johnson, chief executive of Leeds
Chamber of Commerce, was more cautious. 'This year will be a record for
local spending, but then inflation usually ensures that such records are
broken year by year anyway,' he said. 'However, I think there will prove to
have been a genuine increase.'
Mr John Taylor, chief executive of Sheffield Chamber of Trade, said many
people had waited until Monday before starting Christmas shopping in
earnest. 'In the past, sales started picking up at least a week earlier.
Since then, sales have been increasing steadily in the city centre.'
A similar surge was reported in north-east England, although bomb scares
also damped trade in Newcastle. At Eldon Square, Europe's largest city
centre shopping centre, Mr Gordon Allanson, manager, said the surge meant
turnover this year might be slightly ahead of last, rather than between 1
per cent and 2 per cent behind, as he had predicted only 10 days ago.
At nearby Bainbridge, one of the largest department stores in the John Lewis
Partnership, managing director Mr Brian Forbes Turner said this year's trend
towards shoppers seeking value for money and selecting smaller purchases had
continued, but in greater volume in recent days.
Last week, the store finished 1 per cent down on the same week last year.
Saturday sales were well up, however, and this week was proving strong.
China, glassware, jewellery, leather goods, knitwear, lingerie and
computer-related items were all doing well.
At Gateshead's MetroCentre, Mr John Bryson, manager, said the late, strong
turnout of shoppers meant turnover was likely to be up on last year. 'The
British nation has gone on holiday, for a long holiday,' Mr Bryson said.
'They're spending to a surprising degree so close to Christmas. The way
things have gone in the first 2 1/2 days before Christmas has cheered
everybody up.'
Edinburgh stores have had a mixed Christmas because of the EC summit on
December 11 and 12, normally one of the busiest pre-Christmas shopping
weekends.
Mr Andrew Douglas Miller, general manager of Jenners, a privately-owned
department store in Prince's Street, said the summit cost the store business
it might never recoup. 'There was a massive police presence and people were
advised not to bring their cars into town, so many didn't go Christmas
shopping. Trade didn't pick up until about last Thursday. This week,
however, is a lot better than the equivalent week of last year.'
Clydesdale, Scotland's largest independent electrical retail chain, said it
had had a good Christmas in an economy where the effects of recession have
been less dire than in the south. 'We're doing remarkably well compared with
last year,' Mr John Downie, managing director, said.
House of Fraser, which operates eight stores in Scotland, said Christmas
turnover was 21 per cent up on last year. 'Christmas has arrived north of
the border. Our managers are wearing their broadest smiles in a long time.'
Reporting by Neil Buckley, Ian Hamilton Fazey, Chris Tighe and James Buxton
</TEXT>
