<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 92 / Board shake-up at Welsh agency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY MORETON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Welsh Office has announced a shake-up on the board of the heavily
criticised Welsh Development Agency.
After the decision of Dr Gwyn Jones, chairman since 1988, to resign in the
new year, Dr Roy Bichan, non-executive deputy chairman of Simon Robertson
and a consultant to Simon Engineering, has been appointed deputy chairman.
He replaces Sir Donald Walters, who will remain on the board.
Dr Bichan, 50, is chairman of the Welsh Industrial Development Advisory
Board and chairman of the north Wales branch of the CBI. He was chairman of
the Llandudno-based Robertson Group until its takeover by Simon.
The agency, founded in 1976, was severely criticised over financial
procedures by the Commons public accounts committee on December 14. MPs
queried redundancy payments to former employees, reimbursement of car and
petrol expenses to directors, a grant paid to the chairman and a pensions
payment.
Mr Robert Sheldon, Labour chairman of the committee, said there had been
'great laxity' in the agency's affairs.
Three other members of the board whose contracts expire at the end of this
year - Mr Colyn Gardner, former chairman of the DC Gardner group, Mr Tim
Rees, a senior partner in Cardiff with accountants Coopers and Lybrand, and
Mr David Roberts, former chairman of Pilkington Brothers' new business
division - are not being reappointed.
Mr David Hunt, Welsh secretary, said yesterday replacements would be made
after the appointment of a new chairman. 'Once this has been decided I will
wish to consult the chairman about two vacancies which remain."
Mr Hunt is thought likely to look hard at the possibility of appointing a
second woman to the board. Ms Pamela Kirby, managing director of Astra
Pharmaceuticals, the British end of a Swedish producer of ethical drugs, was
the first woman on the board when appointed in December 1991.
