<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 92 / Surprise rise in savings may threaten upturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SHARP rise in personal savings reported yesterday has underlined the depth
of consumer resistance to substantial increases in spending, a development
that may hold back an overall economic upturn.
Britain's economic weakness was also underlined by the decline in wages and
salaries in the third quarter of this year compared with the previous three
months - the first time that those items have seen two successive
quarter-on-quarter drops since government records started in 1955.
Total personal disposable income saw a modest rise between the second and
third quarters. That was partly because of redundancy and dividend payments.
The Central Statistical Office said the savings ratio - personal savings as
a percentage of personal income, less income tax, social security
contributions and other financial transfers - climbed to 12.3 per cent in
the third quarter.
The seasonally adjusted figure was the highest since late 1984, and came
after savings ratios of 11.4 per cent in both the first and second quarters.
It surprised the City, which had expected a third-quarter savings ratio of
about 10 per cent.
Wages and salaries as measured in current prices, unadjusted for inflation,
fell by 0.2 per cent between the second and third quarters to Pounds
74.58bn. That was after a 0.7 per cent drop between the first and second
three-month periods.
The fall in wages and salaries was partly because of falling employment. It
may also have been a reflection of a high Pounds 75.29bn figure for wages
and salaries in the first quarter.
The drop between the second and third quarters in wages and salaries was
offset by an increase in non-wage income and reduced income tax
contributions. That led to personal disposal income growing between the
second and third quarters by 2.2 per cent to Pounds 110.66bn. After
adjusting for inflation, real personal disposable income grew between those
periods by 1.4 per cent. Compared with the corresponding period last year,
it increased in the third quarter by 2.5 per cent.
The CSO said companies' gross trading profits (after deducting stock
appreciation) came to Pounds 19.76bn in the third quarter, little changed on
the second quarter.
</TEXT>
