<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 92 / Commerce creeps into the corporate card: Clay Harris reviews
the good, the bad and the jovial in seasonal greetings from a range of
companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAY HARRIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SENDERS and recipients of corporate Christmas cards, take note: all European
Community cards must be harmonised by 1997. That, anyway, is the message
distributed in the interest of seasonal cheer by the accounting firm
Blackstone Franks.
Judging by this year's crop of corporate cards, harmony is a long way off in
Britain alone, much less the rest of Europe. In choice of subject, and in
addressing the thorny issue of how commercial a card should be, there is a
healthy diversity.
On the eve of the single market, Europe is on the mind of many senders -
sometimes humorously, as with Blackstone Franks and the British Clothing
Industry Association's Euro Snowman which 'must not be taller than 1.8975
metres' - but often mundanely, with the 12 EC members' flags displayed as
tree ornaments or presents. Panasonic Europe plants the flags in a map that
shows almost all the world, except Japan, its home.
The Met Office, more originally, offers a weather map of north-west Europe
showing conditions on Christmas Day in 1892. More senders this year appear
to include a commercial message on their cards.
It can be blunt in the extreme. Opinion Leader Research and VandenBurg
Public Relations emblazon their name or initials on the front without a hint
of the festive season. Few in the motor industry forgo an opportunity to
plug cars (Citroen's card looks like last year's model).
Westland has Father Christmas in an EH101 helicopter. Seagram London
illustrates 'Get into the spirit of Christmas' with bottles of its brands
hanging on a Christmas tree, while Guinness, showing a pint, proclaims: 'Not
everyone's dreaming of a white Christmas.' For his own card, Sir Antony
Tennant, the company's retiring chairman, sent a painting of Hop Pickers
from the Guinness collection.
Perhaps campaigning organisations can be allowed some leeway. Through deft
editing of A Christmas Carol, the Maxwell/AGB Pension Schemes Contributors
Association lets Dickens make its point about the ghost that still haunts
the pensioners. Camra has a go at changes in the brewing industry, adding
wishes for 'a concentrated new year'.
But Northumbrian Environmental Management surely should have drawn the line
somewhere short of featuring Father Christmas delivering a sleigh-full of
parcels labelled 'liquid treatment', 'clinical incineration' and the like.
Its sibling company, Northumbrian Water, reproduced a sylvan view of the
Sunderland Bridge sewage works.
The London Docklands Development Corporation keeps up the thread of its
'Knocker' and 'Docker' ad campaign. The present-giving taste of the former,
of course, makes us shudder - 'five golden 'Eurovision greats' albums . . .
two turtle neck jumpers (nylon)' - while the latter is bang up-to-date, at
least to the late 1980s: 'five golden autumn leaves (pressed) . . . three
French hens (free range)'.
The Financial Times is in no position to condemn commercialism. Its card -
which has sparked a lively internal debate - shows a robin in snow that has
covered all but a pink corner of the FT.
Some of the most successful cards use subtle allusions to the sender's line
of business, literally in the case of Deutsche Bundesbahn's railway in the
snow (pictured). The tree-top fairy (also pictured) casting a familiar legal
shadow is an attractive, clever and distinctive card that does not overtly
push the name of the sender, solicitors Lewis Silkin.
A company as rich as De Beers has another solution. Its card features a
Raoul Dufy painting which the company commissioned for a 1951 advertising
campaign in the US.
An industrial process itself can be made into art. Outokumpu Zinc's card
features a photograph of zinc casting that could be a rushing stream in the
Arctic spring.
Thankfully, there are fewer cards from the fringes of blasphemy this year.
An unfortunate exception comes from the advertising agency Grey London. The
Immaculate Concept, a back-of-the-envelope sketch for an advert, concludes
with 'cut to pack shot' showing baby Jesus in cot. The best religious card
was the wood engraving (pictured) from the Design Council. But the US
investment bank Goldman Sachs shows how good a purely secular card without
any seasonal reference can be, reproducing a painting from its collection by
the British artist Keith Milow.
One way of making a card stand out from rows of cherubim is to give the
recipient something to do. This year one could connect the dots with
Phildrew Ventures, punch out a Christmas tree with ITV, make a turkey pop up
with the PR agency Paternoster Partnership, open the windows on an 'advert
calendar' to reveal names of FCA's clients or don red and green specs to
appreciate the 3-D Father Christmas bursting from a Mills &amp; Allen poster
hoarding.
Finland's paper industry association offers a flimsy disc which, when played
with a gramophone needle, offers 'compliments of the season to all Finnpap
customers wherever in the world you may be'.
Charity cards are now the rule, but PowerGen shows that its support of the
children's books collection at the National Library for the Blind is not
just a gesture. Its greeting is also printed in Braille.
Hartstone Group has it all ways. Its card promotes Happy Kids on the front,
notes inside that royalties on the sale of these products support the
National Association for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children and then says
it will send no further cards.
Beauty is in the eye of the beholder nowhere more than in Christmas cards.
But this beholder has had enough.
Enough Impressionists. Even Old Masters begin to pall unless they are
reproduced as large and sumptuously as those from commodity broker Brandeis
and management consultants Arthur D. Little.
Enough bad puns from public-relations companies.
And enough generic winter scenes of London, especially of Ludgate Hill with
the now-removed railway viaduct. But focusing on a particular corner, as
College Hill Associates does with its history of the City street in which
Dick Whittington is buried, can make a recipient turn again.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
