<DATE>921224
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 92 / Banks take control of Magnet in rescue move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MAIN bank lenders to Magnet yesterday took control of the fitted
kitchens retailer in a move they said would preserve the business and
protect the position of customers.
The banks' decision to put Airedale Holdings, Magnet's heavily indebted
holding company, into administrative receivership almost certainly means
subordinated creditors and shareholders involved in the controversial Pounds
700m management buy-out in 1989 will have to write off their investments.
Most of the investors and lenders have already partially done so.
Bankers said customers and trade creditors would be secure.
Mr John Foulkes, the Magnet chief executive who was brought in by the banks
three years ago, will remain in charge. He will still receive this month a
Pounds 2m bonus payment from Airedale, as agreed when he was appointed to
turn around the company.
GE Capital, a subsidiary of General Electric of the US, is the largest
subordinated creditor, with Pounds 70m outstanding. It is seeking to upgrade
its position through legal action.
Airedale Holdings, owed an estimated Pounds 450m by the Magnet holding
company, will also only retrieve a proportion of their outstanding loans.
They are Bankers Trust, Standard Chartered, Hill Samuel, Bank of Scotland,
Austria's Credit Anstalt, Bank of America, Continental Bank and the
Long-term Credit Bank of Japan.
The banks said their vehicle, Magnet Group, had purchased the Airedale
subsidiary which controls the Magnet business, from the receivers, BDO
Binder Hamlyn, for a sum believed to be in excess of Pounds 10m.
Insiders said about Pounds 25m of the senior debt had been swapped for
equity in the new vehicle. A spokesman for the Magnet Group stressed that
none of the banks had injected any new money.
The banks say they intend to float or sell Magnet Group within two to five
years. The proceeds will be paid as a deferred consideration to Airedale's
receiver, which will pay off its creditors in order of priority. The first
to be paid will be the eight banks which currently control Magnet Group.
Insiders said yesterday that it was highly unlikely that a sale or flotation
would recoup the full Pounds 450m outstanding to senior creditors.
The eight senior lenders to Isosceles safe until May, Page 8
