<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 92 / TUC expected to urge public-sector strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Trades Union Congress is expected to call for a one-day public-sector
strike in February over jobs, pay and the mining industry crisis.
Mining unions yesterday tried to maintain pressure for an immediate
resumption of coal-cutting at the 10 pits earmarked for closure. They argued
leaving them on a stand-by basis might cost Pounds 150m over nine months.
The TUC has been reluctant to urge a full one-day strike because of the
legal complications and the fear of lack of support. But many unions are now
more ready to risk industrial action. They have been encouraged by Monday's
High Court judgment that the pit closure programme had been carried out
unlawfully.
The mining unions and the TUC public-services committee will meet separately
on January 5 to discuss strategy. The TUC said the committee would consider
'synchronised balloting on industrial action with the aim of building
activity around jobs and pay on a date in February'.
Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, yesterday formally
appointed mining consultants Boyds to report on whether British Coal should
proceed with the closure of the 10 earmarked pits.
The High Court ruling called for an independent assessment before any
closure decision was taken. But the unions argue that Boyds is not
sufficiently independent, as it is working for the government on the wider
Department of Trade and Industry review of the closures due in February or
March.
Mr Norman Willis, TUC general secretary, emphasised in a letter to Mr John
Major, the prime minister, that appointing Boyds was 'not a satisfactory
response; not even the letter of the judgment seems to be followed'.
British Coal has agreed to buy 87,000 tonnes of coal from Monktonhall
colliery, near Edinburgh, which it closed five years ago. The colliery is
now leased by miners who ploughed their redundancy money into operating it
as a private pit. A miners' strike in Poland has reduced imports of
house-coal, and the one-year order for Monktonhall has been placed to make
up the shortfall.
</TEXT>
