<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 92 / Money Markets: Boost for futures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRENCH AND German money markets rallied strongly yesterday after the
Bundesbank president was reported as saying that long-term interest rates in
Germany could decline to below 6 per cent during the current phase of
falling rates, writes James Blitz.
The reaction to Mr Helmut Schlesinger's comments in a newspaper interview
was far more muted in the sterling market, because of the pound's
disconnection from the European exchange rate mechanism.
However, at least one commercial bank dealer said the French and German
markets' reaction to Mr Schlesinger's comments yesterday was significant,
and that there were growing hopes of a reduction in official German rates at
the first Bundesbank council meeting of the new year.
'It is the first time anyone can remember Mr Schlesinger saying something
bullish about interest rate cuts,' he added.
In an interview with the Westdeutsche Allgemeine Zeitung yesterday, the
Bundesbank president said he was confident that Germany's inflation rate
could near 3 per cent in 1993 from an average of around 4 per cent in 1992.
But it was unclear from the interview which long-term interest rates Mr
Schlesinger felt could be reduced.
However, the comments triggered 'a rash of bullish feeling' in French and
German markets, according to one dealer. Euromark futures rallied sharply,
with the March contract rising 12 basis points to a close at 92.19. German
cash rates were generally easier, with three-month money in the Euromark
trading at around 8.87 per cent offered, down from around 9.25 per cent as
recently as last Thursday.
French futures rose sharply on Germany's coat-tails, with the March contract
gaining 15 basis points to close at 90.64 and the June contract adding 9
basis points to end at 91.77. The cash market, centre-stage in the battle of
the French franc, was more resistant to change: three-month money was as
high as 12 1/4 per cent yesterday.
The sterling markets were quieter. The Bank of England forecast a large
shortage of Pounds 1.95bn at the start of the day, but trading was difficult
and there was late assistance of Pounds 475m. Cash rates were generally
unchanged, with three-month money closing again at 7 3/16 per cent.
