FT  23 DEC 92 / UK Company News: Thorn sale helps Chrysalis return to black
with Pounds 5.6m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A PROFITABLE exit from a joint venture with Thorn-EMI helped Chrysalis, the
music publishing, communications and media company, return to the black with
pre-tax profits of Pounds 5.63m for the year to August 31, against losses of
Pounds 9.33m.
The result, struck on sales 3 per cent lower at Pounds 65.9m, was enhanced
by the Pounds 9.65m net profit on discontinued activities, taken above the
line. This included the Pounds 11.58m profit from the sale of the company's
stake in Chrysalis Record Companies, to Thorn in November 1991.
Mr Nigel Butterfield, finance director, said that at the operating level,
the company recorded a loss of about Pounds 4.8m. The group again passed the
dividend, which has not been paid since 1989-90. Earnings per share of
26.02p compared with losses of 30.06p.
Worsening conditions in MAM, Chrysalis's fruit machines subsidiary and the
costs of investing in existing businesses were the main reasons behind the
operating losses, said Mr Butterfield. Fruit machines incurred losses of
Pounds 1.8m (Pounds 1.1m) and this business was expected to suffer
substantial losses this year.
Music publishing profits dived from Pounds 1m to Pounds 250,000, due to the
investment of more than Pounds 1m in signing new talent. Recent names
included the Smashing Pumpkins, who have several hits in the US, and the
Sugar Merchants in the UK.
Higher operating costs hit wholesale exports, which fell by Pounds 200,000
to Pounds 500,000.
All other on-going business incurred deeper losses, except property, which
cut its deficit by Pounds 700,000 to Pounds 300,000. However, Mr Butterfield
said that the media businesses had 'turned round profits' in the current
year. Excluding the fruit machine businesses, the group was capable of
achieving healthy profits, he said.
