FT  23 DEC 92 / Garel-Jones to resign as minister for Europe: PM's close
ally to see Maastricht bill through
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Tristan Garel-Jones, the foreign office minister for Europe who has
played a central role in heading off Tory Euro-sceptics' attacks on the
Maastricht treaty, is to resign next year.
He announced his unexpected decision last night, telling Mr John Major, the
prime minister, in a letter: 'You have known for some time that I hanker
after a change.' His decision is a setback for Mr Major who has suffered a
bruising parliamentary session since April's election.
Mr Garel-Jones is expert on the contents of the Maastricht treaty and, from
his past job as a government whip, on tactics for its ratification by
parliament. However, he will remain in office until the bill has completed
its Commons' stages - probably in late spring.
Whitehall colleagues and officials were adamant last night that Mr
Garel-Jones was genuine in his wish to pursue other interests. In his
letter, he wrote: 'I want to spend more time at home and in my constituency.
I also hope to resume some of my personal interests - even perhaps buy some
more pictures.'
Before joining the Foreign Office in 1990 he was a government whip for eight
years, often working gruelling hours. He remains MP for Watford.
For anti-Maastricht MPs his decision was not a cause for regret. Mr Bill
Cash, Tory MP for Stafford, said Mr Garel-Jones was a 'formidable
adversary'.
The timing of the announcement suggests that Mr Garel-Jones, who appeared
unlikely to secure one of the top Cabinet jobs, wanted to make clear his
determination to step down. It reinforced signals from Downing Street that
no reshuffle of Cabinet or other ministerial posts is imminent.
Mr Garel-Jones told the prime minister in 1991 that he wanted to return to
the backbenches after the general election, but was persuaded to stay for
Britain's European Community presidency and the buildup to the Edinburgh EC
summit.
Replying to Mr Garel-Jones, Mr Major said: 'Your contribution at the Foreign
Office, especially during the British presidency, has been immense, and
played a considerable part in the outcome at Edinburgh last week.'
Mr Garel-Jones has a low public profile, but is a close political ally of Mr
Major.
In the past year, Mr Major has seen two other allies leave Whitehall - Mr
Chris Patten, now governor of Hong Kong, and Mr David Mellor, former
National Heritage secretary.
