<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 92 / Credit and debit cards escape scrutiny by MMC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CREDIT and debit card companies have escaped an investigation by the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission into the fees they charge retailers, but
face further scrutiny by Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair
trading.
Sir Bryan announced yesterday he would not refer credit and debit card
markets to the MMC. He said he would inquire into three possible unfair
practices.
The decision was welcomed by banks and retailers who have complained about
charges over the past two years. The most recent complaint over debit card
charges was made by five supermarket chains this summer.
Sir Bryan said Office of Fair Trading inquiries had not found collusion over
fee increases among banks which issue credit and debit cards. There was also
no evidence the issuing banks were making excessive profits.
The most recent controversy over debit card charges was sparked in June when
Asda, Gateway, Safeway, J. Sainsbury and Tesco complained about a rise in
the fee charged on each Switch card transaction from about 5p to 11p.
The fee charged on credit card transactions has narrowed to about 1.5 per
cent of each purchase for big retailers because of increased competition
among banks to carry out processing. This followed the 1989 MMC report on
credit cards.
Sir Bryan said he would review credit and debit card markets in two years.
Meanwhile, he would informally check three practices:
Retailers which accept cards such as Visa and Mastercard are obliged to
honour any issuer's card and are subject to minimum fees on some
transactions. Sir Bryan said he was concerned that this might mean
'inflexible and unresponsive' pricing.
Although retailers can charge different prices for purchases made by credit
cards rather than cheques or cash, this cannot be done for debit and charge
cards. Sir Bryan said this seemed 'an anomaly' and he would ask if it could
be removed.
Only banks are allowed to act as the 'merchant acquirers' which carry out
card processing and transactions on behalf of retailers for a fee. He said
he would ask if more merchant acquirers could enter the market.
Mr Colin Smith, chairman of the committee of retailers which complained
about debit card pricing in June, said retailers looked forward to
co-operating with the director-general in the further inquiries he had
proposed.
Mr Richard Reay-Smith, chief executive of Barclaycard, said the decision was
'a victory for the consumer'. Card operators had demonstrated that card
processing was a very competitive business, and pricing was often below
cost.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
