<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 92 / Better late than never for big stores: Neil Buckley visits
Wimbledon to see how Christmas is bringing out the shoppers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF THIS Christmas sees the beginning of a consumer-led recovery, some
believe it may be sparked by men's guilt.
Ms Khym Hauxwell, department manager for cosmetics at Debenhams in
Wimbledon, says men shop on Christmas Eve 'slightly drunk after a few drinks
at the pub, with a huge guilt complex. They spend a fortune on perfume and
underwear for their wives and girlfriends.'
Even before Christmas Eve, men are more malleable, more easily persuaded by
a sales pitch. Women 'know what they want and tend to stick to it'. Ms
Hauxwell last week persuaded one man who thought he had come in for a bottle
of perfume for his wife to buy a Pounds 285 gift set.
But guilt-stricken men do not make a Christmas. Retailers are hoping for a
rush of buying this week to make up for what most agree has been the late
arrival of Christmas.
At Debenhams in Wimbledon, the chain's newest store and its showcase, there
was a sense of expectation as the shutters went up on Monday and the
sunlight and piped Christmas muzak flooded in from the recently opened
Centre Court shopping centre.
Mr Steven Gaunt, 39, store manager and veteran of three store launches, will
get little rest until Christmas day. Mr Gaunt says this is his 24th
Christmas in the retail trade.
By 8am he and his deputy are at their desks reviewing the trading figures
for the day before. The figures are a closely guarded secret, but the
managers seem pleased.
The first hour is quiet. Grandmothers with toddlers and pushchairs form the
mainstay of the shoppers. Many head for the restaurant, where a full English
breakfast for 99p is one of the best bar-gains.
Behind the scenes, in the storeroom with its yards of clothes racks and
hydraulic shelves, Christmas is in full swing as staff sort through the
first of the day's deliveries - 126 sets of men's clothing each containing
between three and 20 garments.
Most of the year there may be two deliveries a day from Debenhams warehouses
and several others for concessions within the store. In the weeks before
Christmas there may be twice as many, each three times normal size.
Mr Gaunt makes a detailed tour of the store. Fixtures are straightened,
displays prodded and tweaked. A table short of stock is viewed with a
mixture of satisfaction and disapproval. He can tell at a glance what people
are buying. Women's wraps did well yesterday; so did slipper socks and men's
casual shirts.
Upstairs in the toy department are other big sellers - Trolls, dolls with
elfin faces and clumps of brightly coloured hair, and, in what is normally
the hi-fi listening room in the electrical department, video games and home
karaoke machines.
By the time of the management meeting at 11am, the store is starting to
buzz. Mums are led by the hand by small children whose want lists are
blissfully unaffected by the recession. An hour later, they are joined by
workers on their lunch hour. Queues form by the checkouts; there are smiles
from the manage-ment.
As buying begins in earnest, Mr Gaunt reviews the socks and underwear
department. Marks are awarded for presentation and layout; even in the
Christmas rush retailing is an exact science.
There is time only for a microwaved cottage pie in the self-service canteen
before the managers head out to snoop around the shelves of their
competitor, Elys, the independent department store.
On the way there is a chance to review trading elsewhere in the centre.
There are encouraging signs. In spite of the recession, more than 65 per
cent of space in Centre Court has been let, with 70 per cent expected by the
end of January. Shops such as Athena and the Body Shop are teeming.
'People are out today,' Mr Gaunt says with approval. But few shoppers are
carrying the bulging plastic bags traditionally associated with Christmas.
Elys is full of shoppers, but lightly laden ones. The Debenhams spies learn
little except that Elys plans to open on Sunday, January 3. Debenhams does
not.
Back for the afternoon staff meeting, and there is something of a lull in
trading before the next peak around 5pm, when commuters start pouring in
from Wimbledon station. The last three hours could be the busiest of the
day.
By 6pm, Khym Hauxwell is smiling again. She has just persuaded a man to part
with Pounds 585 on perfumes and cosmetics for his wife and daughters. Even
in the depths of a recession, old-fashioned selling skills can pay off.
Retailers are wondering whether those skills will be enough.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
