<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 92 / Businessmen urged to bid for sell-offs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CABINET Office is inviting senior business executives to a conference in
London next month to encourage them to bid for the Pounds 1.5bn of central
government services to be put out to tender before the end of September.
Under the market-testing programme launched last month, more than 44,000
civil servants will have to compete for their jobs against bids from the
private sector.
The government expects to make savings of 25 per cent of the value of the
services put out to tender, even when the contract is won by the existing
staff.
The conference is being held because of fears that business has yet to
recognise the opportunities offered by the 60-fold increase in activities to
be put out to tender.
The government wants several bids for each activity, and hopes that a range
of businesses will be involved.
Ministers are also keen to highlight the extension of market-testing into
activities previously regarded as core Whitehall functions, such as managing
government computers holding criminal records. Other services to be
contracted out include finance, accounting, auditing, payroll, recruitment,
legal services, debt collection, typing and secretarial services, estate and
building management.
A similar event in Birmingham last month staged by the Ministry of Defence
attracted more than 600 companies.
The London conference, on January 18, is being organised along similar
lines, with members of the Cabinet Office efficiency unit explaining the
procedures for putting in bids.
Detailed information will be provided for the first time about the
activities to be market-tested. Representatives from each department will be
available to discuss their department's plans and offer guidance on who to
approach if bidding for a particular activity. More than 20,000 businesses
have been invited.
</TEXT>
