FT  23 DEC 92 / Newspaper industry plans second campaign against possible
VAT on papers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE newspaper industry is planning its second campaign in eight years
against the possible imposition of value added tax on newspapers, Raymond
Snoddy writes.
The industry is increasingly worried that the government will impose VAT on
newspapers and magazines - and possibly books - in one of next year's two
Budgets.
Mr Dugal Nisbet-Smith, director of the Newspaper Society, which represents
local and regional newspapers, said yesterday: 'We have not had a denial
from any minister that this is on the agenda.'
The Newspaper Society has commissioned consultants Price Waterhouse to look
at the impact the imposition of 17.5 per cent VAT on newspapers would have.
During the 1984-85 campaign against VAT, Price Waterhouse said a 15 per cent
rate of VAT would cut circulations by 7 per cent and lead to the closure of
12 or 13 regional dailies and about 100 weekly newspapers.
The society has found a disappointing response in its lobbying of MPs - the
mood may have swung against newspapers in the wake of revelations about some
senior politicians and members of the Royal Family.
The Newspaper Society fears that the imposition of VAT - which could also be
charged on free papers - would amount to as much as Pounds 500m a year.
Relaunching its campaign, the society said it believed 'that sufficient
evidence now existed that VAT on newspapers, books and magazines was again
on the chancellor's Budget agenda'.
</TEXT>
