<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 92 / Major loses his jovial 'Mr Fixit'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Tristan Garel-Jones, the minister for Europe who announced his imminent
resignation yesterday, is not only part-architect, part-pilot of the
Maastricht treaty who passionately pushes the case for Europe. He is also a
hate figure for Tory Euro-sceptics, the target chosen by Maastricht's
opponents when direct attacks on the prime minister smacked of spite and
disloyalty.
He has withstood the jibes and whispering campaigns with relish. Now he has
decided to make a break.
Last night there was nothing to suggest that his reasons for going from next
spring - time to see the Maastricht bill through its Commons stages - were
not genuine. He has a Spanish wife, five children, business interests, a
passion for painting and a house in Spain.
The loss of a senior minister responsible for a central part of government
policy will not help Mr John Major after a bruising six months.
The two have been close allies since they entered politics; the prime
minister has depended on Mr Garel-Jones's skills during a troublesome EC
presidency.
He spent eight years in the Whips office before becoming a foreign minister.
He rose to deputy chief whip, his 'wet' Conservative instincts more than
outweighed - in the eyes of Mrs Margaret Thatcher, the former prime minister
 -by his cunning and badgering prowess.
In 1990 he offered to resign, saying he was fed up with the hours and with
being the only whip who thoroughly understood parliament's complex
procedures. But Mrs Thatcher gave him a job at the Foreign Office that
matched his enthusiasms.
The same year, he was accused by the Tory right of plotting to bring Mrs
Thatcher down. A crucial meeting of ministers was held at his London house
during the leadership bid of Mr Michael Heseltine, now trade and industry
secretary; his version is that the meeting was just drinks with friends.
His joviality does not always compensate for a frantic lifestyle jetting
across Europe. At night he reads the 'red boxes' of official documents in
bed, scribbling witty - sometimes deeply undiplomatic - asides in the
margins.
In spite of the jesting, he does not like Euro-sceptics' charges that he is
'a Euro-freak'. The European Community, he told a fringe meeting at the
Conservative party conference in October, 'is the most frustrating,
pusillanimous organisation you have ever come across'.
He campaigned for Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, to replace Mrs
Thatcher as prime minister. He says it was an act of loyalty - but he is
clearly at ease under Mr Major, whose down-to-earth style matches his own.
Mr Garel Jones first told the prime minister he wanted to step down last
summer, but his love of cut-and-thrust politics makes it hard to see how he
will manage to distance himself completely from the Whitehall machine.
</TEXT>
