FT  23 DEC 92 / Bomb explodes in Tube station
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A BOMB believed to have been planted by the IRA exploded at Hampstead Tube
station yesterday evening. It caused disruption to London Underground
services and subsequent street closures by the police led to severe local
traffic congestion, Jimmy Burns writes.
British Transport Police said the explosion occurred at platform level at
the bottom of a shaft. It happened within 30 minutes of a coded telephone
warning to the Press Association news agency by a man claiming to represent
the IRA. There were no reports of casualties.
The incident represented a departure in the tactics being adopted by the IRA
in its pre-Christmas campaign. Previous IRA attacks affecting the
Underground system in recent months have taken place outside stations or
have involved small incendiary devices placed in carriages before passengers
have boarded trains.
Scotland Yard's anti-terrorist branch and the security service MI5 have
launched anoperation aimed at arresting an estimated three IRA units that
are believed to be operating on the mainland.
