<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 92 / Confusion arises on orimulsion plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE WAS confusion last night over plans for the UK's largest
orimulsion-burning power plant after the plant's owners denied a statement
by the pollution authorities that they had withdrawn their application for
authorisation.
The Pollution Inspectorate said National Power had withdrawn an application
to burn orimulsion at its Pembroke plant and was seeking authority to burn
heavy oil instead. The inspectorate referred to a letter from the manager of
the Pembroke plant on December 21. Orimulsion, developed in Venezuela in the
mid 1980s, is about 70 per cent bitumen by volume mixed with water and an
additive to keep the mixture stable.
National Power said the letter from the plant manager was intended to seek
more time to respond to a call from the inspectorate earlier in October for
stronger environmental safeguards. National Power said it was still
investigating the commercial prospects for orimulsion, although he confirmed
that it was also planned to burn heavy oil.
Oil is currently burned at the 2,000MW Pembroke plant. National Power's
plans to convert it to orimulsion have been denounced by the environmental
lobby, which labels orimulsion 'the filthy fuel'. The fuel became notorious
in August last year after an accident at Richborough power station, in Kent,
left cars corroded by 'acid smuts', a kind of acid rain.
In October, the inspectorate told National Power that it could not approve
the plant unless more environmental measures - which it did not specify -
were adopted.
The power generation industry accepts that orimulsion contains more sulphur
than most oil or coal, but argues that its overall emissions are less
harmful. It is cheaper than domestically produced coal and competes with
imported coal. PowerGen, the smaller of the two power generators, has been
burning orimulsion for several years on an experimental basis without
environmental controls at Richborough and at a power station in Cheshire.
</TEXT>
