<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 92 / Minister's council move overturned
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A DECISION by Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, to close
the London borough of Haringey's own refuse collection service was
overturned by the High Court yesterday.
Two judges ruled that the closure order, due to take effect in the new year,
was legally flawed and must be reconsidered.
Mr Heseltine acted last March, while environment secretary, after
allegations of 'anti-competitive behaviour' by the Labour-controlled council
in awarding itself a contract for refuse collection and street cleaning
work.
Mr Michael Portillo, then local government minister, told parliament the
council had accepted the bid from its own direct service organisation in
spite of two lower bids from the private sector.
Yesterday Lord Justice Evans, sitting with Mr Justice Otton, ruled that Mr
Heseltine had been legally obliged to consider allowing the organisation to
put in a new bid, subject to conditions, before ordering a complete bar.
'There is no evidence that the secretary of state did this, and if he failed
to do so, then in my judgment he erred in law,' the judge said. Haringey
welcomed the ruling.
</TEXT>
