FT  23 DEC 92 / UK Company News: Berlitz clears the way for Japanese bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BERLITZ, the language school and publishing group that was once part of the
late Mr Robert Maxwell's empire, yesterday said it had resolved a number of
outstanding differences with the court-appointed administrators of the
Maxwell Communication Corporation (MCC).
The agreements should help clear the way for the planned takeover of Berlitz
by Fukutake, a Japanese publisher.
The Fukutake deal was contingent upon the resolution of disputes about
financial obligations among Berlitz; MCC, which is operating under US
bankruptcy proceedings; and Macmillan, the publishing subsidiary of MCC.
The issues that were settled yesterday include an agreement under which
Macmillan will transfer to Berlitz 180,000 shares of Berlitz preferred stock
it was holding.
In addition Berlitz will transfer to Macmillan a Dollars 64.6m Macmillan
promissory note it was holding. MCC will then release Berlitz from all
claims against the company. For its part, Berlitz will agree to reduce by
Dollars 58m to Dollars 71m the amount of its claims against MCC regarding
outstanding promissory notes. The companies have also agreed to clarify
certain tax agreements.
Berlitz said the Fukutake deal would be submitted to its shareholders in
January.
MCC has featured in the Berlitz saga because some 56.5 per cent of Berlitz
stock was pledged to banks last year as collateral for loans made to the
late Mr Robert Maxwell. These shares have been the subject of litigation.
When the Fukutake deal is completed Berlitz shareholders will end up with 33
per cent of the company and the Japanese buyer will own the majority 67 per
cent stake.
</TEXT>
