<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 92 / London Stock Exchange: Footsie breaks through to new peak
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANOTHER session of heavy demand for shares across the range of the London
stock market took the FT-SE Index through the 2,800 barrier to a new
all-time peak yesterday. At the close, the Footsie was 18 points up at
2,807.7, after breaking through the previous closing high of 2,792 in early
trading.
Once again, the market was featured by strong buying of the second-tier
stocks. The FT-SE Mid 250 Index outpaced the Footsie by a factor of two,
gaining 33.8, or 1.2 per cent, to 2,817.4.
Traders reported significant support from the institutions, and were borne
out by continued strength in Seaq-reported business at 831.4m shares,
compared with 940.4m on Friday, when retail, or customer, business was worth
Pounds 1.60bn.
Optimism for a revival in the UK economy next year was encouraged by a
report from the Birmingham Chamber of Industry and Commerce which indicated
'slow but steady' recovery in business in this important UK manufacturing
area.
The move into cyclical stocks, likely to benefit quickly from economic
recovery, was reflected in a subdued performance from the blue chip
defensive issues, which lagged behind the rest of the stock market
yesterday. A heavy programme of delayed deals in leading stocks was reported
after the official close.
A shortage of stock led to a strong advance in stock index futures, although
turnover remained thin.
Having opened at 2,818, selling from a leading independent house sent the
March contract on the FT-SE Index into retreat and it fell to a low for the
day of 2,809 at around 10.00am.
However, dealers moving to cover short positions led to a squeeze in March,
and it moved ahead for the rest of the session with demand particularly
strong in the last 90 minutes of trading. March ended at 2,848, up 33 from
Friday's close and around 22 points above its estimated fair value premium
of 19 to cash. Turnover, at around 6,000 lots, was poor.
Volume in the traded options was down from Friday's high figure but still
healthy at 33,811 contracts. The FT-SE 100 option traded 16,945, while a big
trade in Glaxo just before the close made it the most active stock option of
the day.
</TEXT>
