<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow recedes slightly after
Friday's gains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices ended little changed yesterday after investors consolidated
some of the big gains earned in last Friday's 'triple-witching' rally,
writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down just 0.81 at
3,312.46, near its best level of the day. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 lost
0.58 at 440.70, but the Nasdaq composite rose 1.17 to 662.46, another record
high.
Turnover on the New York SE was busy at 226m shares, and declines outscored
rises by 1,019 to 858.
The market's 44-point Dow advance on Friday was primarily the result of
buying related to the 'triple-witching' expiration of stock and stock-index
futures and options, so analysts expected prices to open easier yesterday.
The underlying mood of the market, however, remained optimistic, which
helped prices to pick up from early losses. Observers believe investors are
increasingly confident about the economy and the long-term prospects for
corporate earnings. This upbeat mood has fuelled the recent rally, and
although some institutions had already closed their books for the year, some
analysts were not ruling out further gains in the final days of the year.
IBM dropped a further Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 48 7/8 in turnover of almost
7.4m shares following the announcement that two retired executives were
being rehired to help Mr John Akers, IBM's chairman, run the computer group.
Time Warner firmed Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 29 1/4 in the wake of news that
Mr Steven Ross, the group's chairman, had died of cancer over the weekend,
and that eight senior directors would be leaving at the end of this year in
an apparent culmination of a long boardroom struggle at the entertainment
giant.
USAir dropped Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 11 3/4 as hopes faded that government
authorities would approve the proposed alliance between the carrier and
British Airways. A last-ditch attempt last weekend by Mr John Major, the UK
prime minister, to persuade President George Bush to give the green light
appeared to have failed.
National Health Laboratories plummeted Dollars 5 3/8 to Dollars 17 1/4 in
turnover of 4.8m shares after the company pleaded guilty to charges of
healthcare fraud and agreed to pay Dollars 110.4m to settle claims involving
clinical testing procedures and the Medicare programme.
On the American Stock Exchange, Ivax Corp plunged Dollars 5 7/8 to Dollars
29 in turnover of 1.5m shares after PaineWebber, the Wall Street broking
house, had downgraded the stock from 'buy' to 'attractive'.
On the Nasdaq market, Ross Cosmetics climbed Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 12
after reporting fiscal first-quarter income of 22 cents a share, up from 17
cents registered a year earlier.
Canada
TORONTO stocks ended softer, weighed down by losses in Canadian gold shares
and a round of profit-taking following last week's sharp gains.
The TSE 300 index shed 10 points to 3,310.4 and declining issues outnumbered
rises by 350 to 301 after volume of 42.1m shares valued at CDollars 358.4m.
The gold and silver share index, taking its cue from a USDollars 3 an ounce
retreat by bullion futures, dipped 101.6 to 5,225.7.
</TEXT>
